    <fr:title text="Distance Measure">Distance Measure</fr:title>
    <fr:taxon>Definition</fr:taxon>
    <fr:date>
      <fr:year>2025</fr:year>
      <fr:month>5</fr:month>
      <fr:day>26</fr:day>
    </fr:date>
    <fr:authors>
      <fr:author>Long Nguyen</fr:author>
    </fr:authors>
  </fr:frontmatter>
  <fr:mainmatter>
    <fr:p>A distance measure, or metric, is a function that defines a measure of distance between elements of a set. In a <fr:link type="local" href="FA-000G.xml" addr="FA-000G" title="Metric Space">metric space</fr:link>, a distance function <fr:tex display="inline"><![CDATA[d]]></fr:tex> satisfies the following properties for all points <fr:tex display="inline"><![CDATA[x]]></fr:tex>, <fr:tex display="inline"><![CDATA[y]]></fr:tex>, and <fr:tex display="inline"><![CDATA[z]]></fr:tex> in the space:</fr:p>
    <fr:ul><fr:li>Non-negativity: <fr:tex display="inline"><![CDATA[d(x,y) \geq  0]]></fr:tex></fr:li>
<fr:li>Identity of indiscernibles: <fr:tex display="inline"><![CDATA[d(x,y) = 0]]></fr:tex> if and only if <fr:tex display="inline"><![CDATA[x = y]]></fr:tex></fr:li>
<fr:li>Symmetry: <fr:tex display="inline"><![CDATA[d(x,y) = d(y,x)]]></fr:tex></fr:li>
<fr:li>Triangle inequality: <fr:tex display="inline"><![CDATA[d(x,z) \leq  d(x,y) + d(y,z)]]></fr:tex></fr:li></fr:ul>
  </fr:mainmatter>
